'''Bimkom''' - Planners for Planning Rights ({{lang-he|במקום}}) is an [[Israel]]i non-profit organization established in May 1999 by [[Land use planning|planners]] and architects seeking to address human rights concerns in their spatial and urban designs. Bimkom's goals include retroactively legalizing [[illegal construction]] in Arab neighborhoods<ref>http://www.haaretz.com/news/j-lem-municipality-advancing-plan-to-build-1-900-apartments-for-arabs-1.230076 Jerusalem advancing building plan for Arabs</ref> and promoting greater public involvement in the planning process. Its strategies include community-planning activities, educational activities, and public out-reach activities.

Bimkom has undertaken projects in the [[Negev Desert]] of southern Israel to aid [[Bedouin]] living in unrecognized villages. A plan for building 1,900 housing units in the Arab village of [[Isawiya]], northwest of the road to [[Ma'ale Adumim]] was approved by the Jerusalem Municipality in 2005. According to then Jerusalem mayor [[Uri Lupolianski]], it is one of 50 plans under way for improving the status of [[East Jerusalem]] residents and providing a solution for the acute housing shortage. <ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/907562.html J'lem municipality advancing plan to build 1,900 apartments for Arabs - Haaretz - Israel News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

