'''Dielectric breakdown model (DBM)''' is a macroscopic [[mathematical model]] combining the [[diffusion-limited aggregation]] model with [[electric field]]. It was developed by Niemeyer, Pietronero, and Weismann in 1984.<ref>"Fractal Dimension of Dielectric Breakdown" by L. Niemeyer, L. Pietronero*, and H. J. Wiesmann, Phys. Rev. Lett. 52, 1033–1036 (1984)</ref> It describes the patterns of [[dielectric breakdown]] of solids, liquids, and even gases, explaining the formation of the branching, [[self-similar]] [[Lichtenberg figure]]s.
