===Other storms=== There were several other tropical cyclones that formed in one basin, dissipated, and re-developed. In addition, there were tropical cyclones that developed and entered another basin briefly or at a weak intensity, however, they were not recognized as an Atlantic-Pacific crossover hurricane. In chronological order from most recent to earliest, they are: *The remnants of [[Hurricane Janet]] in [[1955 Atlantic hurricane season|1955]] later led to the formation of an unnamed tropical storm in the East Pacific on October&nbsp;1;<ref name=adv>{{cite web|title=Bulletins and Advisories Issued by Weather Bureau Airport Station, San Juan, Puerto Rico, Weather Bureau Office, Miami, Florida, and Weather Bureau Office, New Orleans, Louisiana on Hurricane "Janet"|url=http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/hurricanes/Qc9452j26b81955.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=United States Weather Bureau|accessdate=April 28, 2013|author=United States Department of Commerce|year=1955}}</ref> the newly generated tropical cyclone later brought rains to the southwestern United States.<ref name="Tech Memo">{{cite journal|title=The Effects of Tropical Cyclones on the Southwestern United States|journal=NOAA Technical Memorandum|date=August 1986|url=http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/noaa_documents/NWS/NWS_WR/TM_NWS_WR_197.pdf|accessdate=July 1, 2013|publisher=National Weather Service Western Region}}</ref> *[[Hurricane Hattie]] in 1961 developed in the Atlantic, and crossed into the Pacific, eventually re-developing into Tropical Storm Simone in the Pacific. It also appeared that remnants of Simone re-emerged into the Atlantic basin to develop into Tropical Storm Inga. However, the viewpoint of U.S. Weather Bureau Office was that "the remnants of Hattie developed into neither Simone nor Inga.<ref>http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/mwr/090/mwr-090-03-0107.pdf</ref> *[[1971 Atlantic hurricane season#Tropical Storm Chloe|Tropical Storm Chloe]] in 1971 made landfall in the Yucatán Peninsula and dissipated soon after. Its remnants continued into the Eastern Pacific and developed into [[Hurricane Lily (1971)|Hurricane Lily]], which made landfall in southwest Mexico. *[[Hurricane Cosme (1989)|Hurricane Cosme]] in 1989 crossed from the Pacific and dissipated over northern Mexico. Its remnants contributed to the development of [[Tropical Storm Allison (1989)|Tropical Storm Allison]] in the Atlantic. *[[Tropical Storm Bret (1993)|Tropical Storm Bret]] from 1993 retained its circulation and was designated Tropical Depression Eight-E upon reaching the Pacific. The depression dissipated, reorganized, and became [[1993 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Greg|Hurricane Greg]]. *[[Tropical Depression Nine (2001)|Tropical Depression Nine]] in 2001 made landfall in Nicaragua and degenerated into a tropical wave. The wave later regenerated into a tropical depression that became [[Hurricane Juliette (2001)|Hurricane Juliette]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Miles B. Lawrence and Michelle M. Mainelli |publisher=National Hurricane Center |date=November 30, 2001 |accessdate=June 28, 2009 |title=Hurricane Juliette Tropical Cyclone Report |url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/2001juliette.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006122021/http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/2001juliette.html |archivedate=October 6, 2008 |df= }}</ref> *[[Hurricane Iris]] of 2001 in the Atlantic Ocean triggered the formation of [[2001 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Storm Manuel|Tropical Storm Manuel]] in the Pacific. *[[Tropical Storm Earl (2004)|Tropical Storm Earl]] in 2004 dissipated in the southeast Caribbean Sea, but regenerated into [[2004 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Frank|Hurricane Frank]] in the East Pacific. *[[Tropical Storm Alma]] of 2008 formed off of the West Coast of Costa Rica, made landfall in Nicaragua with speeds up to {{convert|100|km/h}}. The storm soon dissipated. A day later the storm's remnants after encountering a pair of two [[tropical wave]]s regenerated on Nicaragua's east coast into [[Tropical Storm Arthur (2008)|Tropical Storm Arthur]] with sustained winds of {{convert|75|km/h|abbr=on}} and again made landfall in Nicaragua. It is not considered as crossover over as the initial storm had dissipated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2008/al01/al012008.discus.001.shtml|title=Tropical Storm ARTHUR|website=www.nhc.noaa.gov}}</ref> *[[2012 Atlantic hurricane season#Hurricane Ernesto|Hurricane Ernesto]] of 2012 developed near the [[Lesser Antilles]]. The system weakened to a low-pressure area in Mexico and its remnants moved into the eastern Pacific and developed into [[2012 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Storm Hector|Tropical Storm Hector]]. *[[Hurricane Barbara (2013)|Hurricane Barbara]] of 2013 made landfall in southwest Mexico and dissipated before reaching the Gulf of Mexico. The remnants of Barbara and a cyclonic gyre led to the formation of a broad area of low pressure, which later became [[Tropical Storm Andrea (2013)|Tropical Storm Andrea]] over the central Gulf of Mexico. *[[Tropical Storm Trudy (2014)|Tropical Storm Trudy]] of 2014 made landfall in southern [[Mexico]], its remnants emerged into the Bay of Campeche and subsequently developed into [[Tropical Storm Hanna (2014)|Tropical Storm Hanna]] in the Atlantic. *The remnant moisture from [[Hurricane Earl (2016)|Hurricane Earl]] of 2016 interacted with a disturbance on the Pacific coast of Mexico, which contributed to the formation of [[2016 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Storm Javier|Tropical Storm Javier]] in the eastern Pacific. *The remnants of [[Tropical Storm Bret (2017)|Tropical Storm Bret]] of 2017 traversed over Central America and emerged into the eastern Pacific, which led to the formation of [[2017 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Dora|Hurricane Dora]]. *Also in 2017, [[Hurricane Franklin]] made landfall in the Mexican state of [[Veracruz]]; its remnants moved across Mexico during the following day and emerged into the eastern Pacific, later developing into [[2017 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Storm|Tropical Storm Jova]]. *Later that year, [[Hurricane Katia (2017)|Hurricane Katia]] made landfall in Mexico and was then downgraded to a remnant low; its remnants crossed into the Pacific Ocean, where it regenerated into [[2017 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Otis|Hurricane Otis]].
==Naming conventions== {{main|History of tropical cyclone naming}} Prior to 2000, storms were renamed after crossing from the Gulf of Mexico into the Eastern Pacific. At the 22nd hurricane committee in 2000 it was decided that tropical cyclones that moved from the Atlantic to the Eastern Pacific basin and vice versa would no longer be renamed.<ref name="HC 2000">{{cite report |format=PDF |url=http://www.wmo.ch/web/www/TCP/Reports/FINAL%20REP-2000-HC-22.pdf |title=RA IV Hurricane Committee 24th Session |type=Final Report |date=2000 |archivedate=June 30, 2013 |author=RA IV Hurricane Committee |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6HlyVPYLf?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20030519153637/http%3A//www.wmo.ch/web/www/TCP/Reports/FINAL%20REP-2000-HC-22.pdf |page=5 |accessdate=April 17, 2015 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> [[Hurricane Otto (2016)|Hurricane Otto]] in 2016 was the first storm to cross from one basin to another to apply under this rule.
