{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
The '''Neelanjali Ruby''', at 1,370 [[Carat (unit)|carats]] (274 g), is the world's largest double-star [[ruby]].
A ruby is known as a star ruby if it contains an [[asterism (gemmology)|asterism]] (distinctive star-shaped light refraction) in the gem. The Neelanjali Ruby is the world's largest star ruby with a 12-point asterism, which is commonly denoted as a double-star ruby.
The ''Neelanjali'' ruby, along with the Rajarathna ruby'','' was used as a [[Shiva lingam]] and was worshipped for centuries in the home of the family which owned it. The ruby belongs to G. Vidyaraj, the scion of the [[Aravidu dynasty]] which was the last of the four imperial lineages to rule the [[Vijayanagara empire]]. It is reported to be in safe keeping in [[Bangalore]], [[India]].
